<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<archimate:ArchimateModel xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:archimate="http://www.archimatetool.com/archimate" name="sAIm - Views &amp; Themes" id="id-saim-views-e3d5f2b1a9c7-6f4e2d8b1a5c" version="5.0.0">

  <!-- VIEW 1: SYSTEM OVERVIEW -->
  <folder name="Views" id="id-views-folder" type="other">
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="1. System Overview" id="id-view-system-overview" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: High-level business-to-infrastructure view showing how Claude Code user interacts with PAI system

LAYOUT:
- Top row: Business actors and roles (Claude Code User, System Operator)
- Middle: Core runtime (Claude Code Harness, Hook System, Skills Framework)
- Bottom: Infrastructure services and dashboards

KEY ELEMENTS:
- Claude Code User (business actor)
- System Operator (business role)
- Code Assistance function
- System Automation function
- Claude Code Harness (app component)
- 9 Infrastructure Services (voice-server, memory-system, awareness, observability, service-monitor, discord, etc.)

RELATIONSHIPS:
- User uses Claude Code Harness
- Harness coordinates all services
- Services provide operational capabilities

INSIGHTS:
Shows complete system topology without implementation details. Good for stakeholder briefings.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 2: CORE RUNTIME ARCHITECTURE -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="2. Core Runtime Architecture" id="id-view-core-runtime" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: Detailed view of the Claude Code session lifecycle and core components

LAYOUT:
- Left: Claude Code Harness (entry point)
- Center: Hook System with 6 lifecycle hooks
- Right: Skills Framework, Agent System, History System

COMPONENTS:
Hook Layer:
- SessionStart Hook → Load CORE context, resolve PAI_DIR
- PreToolUse Hook → Validate permissions
- PostToolUse Hook → Capture to history, extract memory
- Stop Hook → Voice notification
- UserPromptSubmit Hook → Log and update memory
- Security Validator Hook → Enforce protected files

Execution Flow:
- Skills Framework (28+ composable packages)
- Agent System (27 specialized personas)
- History System (UOCS - Universal Output Capture)

RELATIONSHIPS:
- Each hook flows to its handler
- Hooks activate skills
- Skills delegate to agents
- Agents record to history

INSIGHTS:
This is the heartbeat of sAIm. Every interaction passes through these hooks.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 3: HOOK SYSTEM DETAILED -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="3. Hook System Detailed" id="id-view-hooks-detailed" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: Deep dive into hook execution sequence and their responsibilities

LAYOUT:
Vertical timeline showing 6 hooks in execution order:
1. SessionStart → config-loader, path-resolver
2. UserPromptSubmit → memory-capture
3. PreToolUse → security-validator
4. Tool Execution
5. PostToolUse → history capture, memory-capture
6. Stop → voice-client notification

SEQUENCES:
Session Initialization (SessionStart):
  → Resolve PAI_DIR (4-tier fallback: Explicit → HOME → Service → os.homedir())
  → Load .agent/settings.json
  → Validate protected files
  → Load CORE skill
  → Initialize memory cache
  → Return context object

Tool Execution (PreToolUse → Execute → PostToolUse):
  → Validate tool permissions
  → Check protected files won't commit
  → Approve/block
  → Execute tool
  → Capture output to history
  → Extract facts (if memory enabled)
  → Build associations

RELATIONSHIPS:
Each hook is triggered by Claude Code lifecycle event
Hooks are isolated TypeScript modules
Each hook validates its own environment

INSIGHTS:
Hook execution is sequential, predictable, and auditable. Total overhead ~200ms per cycle.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 4: INFRASTRUCTURE SERVICES ARCHITECTURE -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="4. Infrastructure Services" id="id-view-infra-services" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: All background services, dashboards, and service dependencies

LAYOUT:
Organized by service type:

Core Services:
- Voice Server (PORT 8888) → Text-to-speech with Python sidecar
- Memory System (PORT 4242) → Semantic memory with extraction
- Awareness Dashboard (4100 backend, 5173 frontend) → Operations briefing

Monitoring &amp; Observability:
- Observability Dashboard (PORT 5172) → Real-time agent activity
- Service Monitor (PORT 6000 server, 5175 client) → PAI service health

Remote Control:
- Discord Remote Control → Discord bot interface + memory dashboard

Utilities:
- Markdown Editor (PORT 4444) → Web-based markdown viewer

RELATIONSHIPS:
- Each service has independent lifecycle
- Services communicate via HTTP/REST APIs
- Services emit webhooks for events
- Service Monitor tracks health of all

DEPLOYMENT:
- macOS: launchd plist files
- Linux: systemd unit files
- All grouped under pai-infrastructure.target

INSIGHTS:
All services are optional. Core Claude Code functionality works standalone. Services enhance capabilities incrementally.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 5: API &amp; INTEGRATION LAYER -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="5. API &amp; Integration Layer" id="id-view-api-integration" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: All REST APIs, webhooks, and inter-service communication patterns

LAYOUT:
Two-layer communication:

Synchronous APIs (Request-Response):
- Voice Server API → POST /api/speak, POST /api/notify, GET /health
- Memory System API → POST /memory/extract, GET /memory/search, GET /api/graph
- Awareness Dashboard API → GET /api/briefing, POST /api/operations/task
- Observability Dashboard API → GET /api/agents, WebSocket /ws/agents
- Service Monitor API → GET /api/services, POST /api/services/:name/start|stop|restart
- Discord Remote Control API → !sam commands (help, agent list, memory search, etc.)
- Claude Code Hooks API → SessionStart, PreToolUse, PostToolUse, Stop callbacks

Asynchronous Webhooks (Event-Driven):
- memory.extraction.complete (PostToolUse hook triggers extraction)
- memory.consolidation.complete (Weekly cycle)
- operations.task.status_changed (Task updates)
- infrastructure.service.status_changed (Service state)
- orchestration.agent.completed (Agent finishes)
- voice.speech.complete (Text-to-speech done)
- awareness.briefing.generated (Briefing ready)

RELATIONSHIPS:
- Hooks call APIs synchronously (PreToolUse → security validation)
- APIs emit webhooks asynchronously (extraction → bot notification)
- Webhooks trigger downstream actions (briefing generated → Discord alert)

PATTERNS:
Request Retry: Exponential backoff (3.5s, 7.5s, 15s)
Timeout: 30s for most APIs
Error Codes: 400 (client), 503 (unavailable)
Authentication: Optional (env vars for API keys)

INSIGHTS:
Clean separation between sync and async communication. All APIs document error codes and retry strategies.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 6: DATA LAYER &amp; PERSISTENCE -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="6. Data Layer &amp; Persistence" id="id-view-data-layer" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: All databases, data storage, and data lifecycle

LAYOUT:
Database inventory organized by purpose:

Semantic Memory:
- Memory System DB (SQLite) → facts, associations, sessions, insights
  Tables: facts (id, text, type, confidence, activation_score)
           associations (source_fact_id, target_fact_id, weight)
           insights (title, description, confidence)
  Consolidation: Weekly dedup, pruning, surfacing insights
  Activation: ACT-R model scoring

Episodic Memory:
- Discord Remote Control DB → conversation history, commands, tasks
  Retention: 7-day TTL with weekly rotation

Operational State:
- Awareness Dashboard DB → tasks, briefings, operations, recommendations
- Observability Dashboard DB → sessions, agents, messages, events (90-day retention)

Configuration:
- Settings Files (.agent/settings.json, .agent/settings.local.json) → Hook definitions, permissions, env vars
- Protected Files Manifest (.sam-protected.json) → Forbidden patterns enforcement

History &amp; Audit:
- History System (UOCS) → File-based structured naming
  Pattern: YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_[PROJECT]_[TYPE]_[HIERARCHY]_[DESCRIPTION].md

RELATIONSHIPS:
- Each service owns its database (no cross-database dependencies)
- History system is append-only (no deletes)
- Memory consolidation runs weekly (scheduled job)
- Observability archives after 90 days

BACKUP STRATEGY:
- Daily snapshot: memory.db → .agent/backups/memory-*.db
- Manual: CSV export before archival
- Disaster recovery: Restore from backup, reconcile state

INSIGHTS:
Multi-database architecture provides isolation. Semantic memory separate from episodic memory. No shared database lock contention.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 7: SECURITY &amp; GOVERNANCE MODEL -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="7. Security &amp; Governance" id="id-view-security-governance" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: All security controls, validation, and governance mechanisms

LAYOUT:
Defense-in-depth approach:

Protected Files Validation:
- .sam-protected.json manifest defines forbidden patterns:
  * API keys (ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, VOICE_API_KEY, etc.)
  * Personal emails (jayson.cavendish@gmail.com, etc.)
  * Private paths (/Users/delphijc, $HOME references)
  * Credentials (passwords, OAuth tokens)
  * Session IDs and auth tokens
- PreToolUse hook runs: bun .claude/hooks/validate-protected.ts --staged
- Blocks commit if forbidden patterns detected
- Exception files whitelist (e.g., start.sh may contain env refs)

Git Isolation:
- Strict repo identity verification:
  1. git rev-parse --show-toplevel (confirm expected root)
  2. git remote get-url origin (confirm expected remote)
  3. Never: git add . or git add -A
  4. Always: Scope operations to single project
- Protected files validation before every commit
- Two-repository model:
  * Private (~/.claude): secrets, personal data, voice IDs (NEVER public)
  * Public (sAIm repo): sanitized template, no personal data

Tool Permissions Model:
- Global permissions (all tools)
- User overrides (personal settings)
- Per-tool granularity (specific tools)
- Permission types: Bash, Read, Write, Edit, Grep, Glob, WebFetch, WebSearch, Agent, Skill

Hook Security Context:
- Execution: Within Claude Code harness (same user, full file access)
- Safety: TypeScript strict mode (tsc --noEmit)
- Validation: Dynamic path resolution (no hardcoded paths)
- Error handling: Never silently fail, always log

RELATIONSHIPS:
- All tool execution flows through PreToolUse validation
- All commits blocked if protected files found
- All hooks must pass TypeScript strict mode
- All API requests validated at boundary

INSIGHTS:
Multi-layered security: validation at commit time, tool time, and hook time. Supply chain protection via language policy (Bash/Go/Bun only).
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 8: DEPLOYMENT &amp; SERVICE MANAGEMENT -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="8. Deployment &amp; Management" id="id-view-deployment-management" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: Service lifecycle, deployment patterns, and operational procedures

LAYOUT:
Dual-platform service management:

macOS (launchd):
- Service definitions: ~/Library/LaunchAgents/ (plist files)
- Service grouping: Manually load/unload multiple services
- Commands:
  launchctl load com.pai.*.plist (start)
  launchctl unload com.pai.*.plist (stop)
  launchctl list | grep pai (status)
  log stream --predicate 'process contains pai' (logs)
- Auto-start: RunAtLoad=true in plist

Linux (systemd):
- Service definitions: ~/.config/systemd/user/ (unit files)
- Service grouping: pai-infrastructure.target (start all)
- Commands:
  systemctl --user start pai-infrastructure.target (start all)
  systemctl --user status SERVICE (status)
  systemctl --user restart SERVICE (restart)
  journalctl --user -u SERVICE.service -n 50 (logs)
  systemctl --user enable SERVICE.service (auto-start)
- Auto-start: WantedBy=default.target in unit file

Service Lifecycle:
1. Service definition created (plist or systemd unit)
2. Service registered with system (launchctl load or systemctl daemon-reload)
3. Service started (manual or auto-start on boot)
4. Service health monitored (periodic checks)
5. Service logs captured (system journal)
6. Service restarted on failure (configurable)
7. Service stopped (manual unload or disable)

Port Allocation &amp; Restrictions:
Safe ranges: 4100-4999, 5170-5199, 8800-8899
Unsafe ports (blocked by Chromium): 6000 (X11)
Assigned ports:
- 4100: Awareness backend
- 4242: Memory System
- 4444: Markdown Editor
- 5172: Observability Dashboard
- 5173: Awareness frontend
- 5175: Service Monitor client
- 8888: Voice Server

RELATIONSHIPS:
- All services grouped under pai-infrastructure.target (Linux)
- Services registered with system manager at install time
- Service Monitor dashboard tracks all services
- Discord bot receives service status webhooks

INSIGHTS:
Centralized service management via system manager. No custom process supervision needed. Portable across macOS and Linux.
"/>

    <!-- VIEW 9: PROCESS FLOWS &amp; ORCHESTRATION -->
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="9. Process Flows &amp; Orchestration" id="id-view-process-flows" documentation="
DIAGRAM PURPOSE: End-to-end process flows showing how components interact across use cases

LAYOUT:
Six critical process flows:

FLOW 1: New Session Initialization (Timeline: ~500ms)
1. Claude Code starts new session
2. SessionStart hook triggered
3. load-core-context.ts executes:
   a. Resolve PAI_DIR (4-tier fallback)
   b. Load .agent/settings.json
   c. Validate protected files config
   d. Load CORE skill context
4. Configuration Loader merges settings.local.json overrides
5. Memory Cache initialized with session context
6. Path Resolver ready for dynamic path lookups
7. Session ready for user interaction

FLOW 2: Tool Execution (Timeline: Tool time + ~200ms overhead)
1. User requests tool execution
2. PreToolUse hook validation:
   a. Check tool in allowed list
   b. Validate protected files won't commit
   c. Approve or block with reason
3. If approved, execute tool
4. PostToolUse hook capture:
   a. Save output to history
   b. Extract facts (if memory enabled)
   c. Build associations
   d. Create structured history entry
5. Tool cycle complete

FLOW 3: Memory Extraction (Timeline: &lt;1s per extraction)
Triggered: PostToolUse hook (if ENABLE_MEMORY_HOOKS=true)
1. memory-capture.ts extracts facts from tool output
2. HTTP POST /memory/extract with transcript
3. Memory System processing:
   a. Run 12 fact extraction patterns
   b. Compute confidence scores
   c. Build temporal/topic associations
   d. Store in SQLite
4. Webhook: memory.extraction.complete
5. Consumers update state:
   a. Discord bot logs to dashboard
   b. Sam session enriches context
6. Weekly consolidation:
   a. Deduplicate facts
   b. Prune low-confidence entries
   c. Surface insights
   d. Webhook: consolidation.complete

FLOW 4: Agent Delegation (Timeline: 5s-2m depending on agent work)
1. Skill initiates delegation via Agent tool
2. Agent spawned with specific permissions
3. Agent executor receives task + context
4. Agent processes work (sequential, parallel, or nested)
5. Agent completes work
6. SubagentStop hook:
   a. Log completion to observability DB
   b. Capture output to history
   c. Update task status
   d. Webhook: agent.completed
7. Task runner receives webhook:
   a. Update task record
   b. Notify Discord (if configured)
   c. Trigger follow-up (if needed)
8. Results merged into main session

FLOW 5: Service Health Monitoring (Timeline: 1-2s per service, &lt;5s total)
Trigger: Manual or periodic (30s interval)
1. Service Monitor polls each service:
   a. GET /health endpoint
   b. Check systemctl status (if systemd)
   c. Measure response time
2. Aggregate results
3. If status changed:
   a. Webhook: service.status_changed
   b. Discord bot notified
   c. Observability dashboard updated
4. If service down &gt;5 minutes:
   a. Auto-restart attempt (configurable)
   b. Log incident to history
   c. Voice notification alert

FLOW 6: Discord Command Processing (Timeline: 500ms-3s)
1. User sends !sam command to Discord
2. Command parser identifies command and args
3. Permission check against user role
4. Command executor routes:
   a. !sam agent list → Query observability API
   b. !sam service status → Query service-monitor
   c. !sam memory search → Query memory-system
   d. !sam briefing daily → GET /api/briefing
   e. !sam logs → GET /api/logs/:service
5. Format response (embed, thread, code block)
6. Send to Discord channel
7. Log command to discord.db

RELATIONSHIPS:
- Flows share common components (hooks, APIs, webhooks)
- Flows are non-blocking (async where possible)
- Flows are composable (can chain multiple flows)
- Flows include error handling and rollback

INSIGHTS:
Each flow is well-defined with clear entry/exit points. Error handling is explicit at each step. Total system latency is optimized for interactive use (SessionStart ~500ms, Tool execution ~200ms overhead).
"/>
  </folder>

  <!-- PROFESSIONAL THEME DEFINITIONS -->
  <folder name="Themes" id="id-themes-folder" type="other">
    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="Color Scheme: sAIm Professional" id="id-theme-colors" documentation="
THEME: sAIm Professional (Architecture-Appropriate Colors)

This theme emphasizes the layered architecture of sAIm with semantic color coding.

Business Layer (Top) - CYAN (#00BCD4)
- Claude Code User
- System Operator
- Business Functions
- Business Processes
→ Represents strategic/user-facing concerns

Application Layer (Middle) - PURPLE (#9C27B0)
- Claude Code Harness
- Hook System
- Skills Framework
- Agent System
- History System
→ Represents core runtime and orchestration

Infrastructure Layer (Bottom) - ORANGE (#FF9800)
- Voice Server
- Memory System
- Awareness Dashboard
- Observability Dashboard
- Service Monitor
→ Represents operational services

Technology Stack - TEAL (#009688)
- Bun Runtime
- Bash Scripting
- Go Backend
- TypeScript
- SQLite
→ Represents implementation technology

Security Elements - RED (#F44336)
- Protected Files Validation
- Hook Security Context
- Tool Permissions
- Git Isolation
→ Represents security controls

Data &amp; State - BLUE (#2196F3)
- Memory Cache
- Configuration Loader
- Databases
- History Files
→ Represents persistence and state

API &amp; Webhooks - GREEN (#4CAF50)
- REST APIs
- Webhook System
- Event-Driven Communication
→ Represents inter-service communication

Relationships:
- ServingRelationship: Solid line, weight 2pt
- FlowRelationship: Directional arrow, weight 1.5pt
- AssignmentRelationship: Dashed line, weight 1pt

Font:
- Elements: Arial 11pt
- Labels: Arial 10pt bold
- Documentation: Arial 9pt italic

Layout Guidelines:
- Business layer at top
- Application layer in middle
- Infrastructure layer at bottom
- Left-to-right flow for information
- Vertical alignment for hierarchy
- Consistent spacing (20px between elements)

Emphasis:
- Critical path elements: Bold outline (2pt border)
- Optional components: Dashed outline
- Active state: Solid fill + shadow
- Inactive state: Light gray fill
"/>

    <element xsi:type="archimate:DiagramModel" name="Visual Hierarchy &amp; Grouping" id="id-theme-hierarchy" documentation="
HIERARCHY LEVELS:

Level 1 (Broadest): System Overview
- Single diagram showing all layers
- Business → Application → Infrastructure
- Focus: stakeholder communication

Level 2 (Detailed): Component View
- Individual layers (Business, Application, Infrastructure)
- Relationships within layer
- Focus: technical stakeholders

Level 3 (Deepest): Process View
- Specific workflows (Session, Tool Execution, etc.)
- Detailed interactions
- Focus: implementation teams

GROUPING STRATEGY:

By Layer:
- Business Folder (actors, roles, functions)
- Application Folder (components, frameworks)
- Infrastructure Folder (services, databases)
- Technology Folder (runtime, languages)

By Capability:
- Hook System (lifecycle events)
- Skills Framework (composable capabilities)
- Agent System (delegation patterns)
- Memory System (semantic extraction)
- Service Management (deployment)

By Concern:
- Security (validation, permissions, isolation)
- Data (databases, persistence, caching)
- Integration (APIs, webhooks, communication)
- Operations (monitoring, health checks, runbooks)

LABELING:

Element Names: Descriptive, no abbreviations
Example: 'Claude Code Harness' not 'CCH' or 'Harness'

Relationship Labels: Action-oriented verbs
- 'Triggers', 'Activates', 'Delegates', 'Records'
- 'Validates', 'Captures', 'Notifies', 'Integrates'

Documentation:
- Hover text: Technical details
- Full documentation: Complete specification
- Examples: Code snippets where applicable

SPACING &amp; ALIGNMENT:

Horizontal: 60px between related elements
Vertical: 40px between layers
Margins: 20px from diagram edge

Groups:
- Related elements clustered (20px internal)
- Group separation: 40px
- Folder visual boundary with border

EMPHASIS:

Critical Path (hot path):
- Claude Code User → Harness → Hooks → Skills → Agents
- Highlight: bold (2pt) outline, solid fill

Optional Components:
- Memory System, Discord Bot, Dashboards
- Highlight: dashed outline, light fill

Data Flow (high volume):
- PostToolUse → History → Memory Extraction
- Highlight: directional arrows, thicker lines

Infrequent Events:
- Service failures, manual management
- Highlight: red outline, warning color
"/>
  </folder>
</archimate:ArchimateModel>
